* Provide an easy way to exit the web-server:
  - [x] In CLI, by entering "exit" or "quit"
  - [x] In the webpage, with an "Exit" button
The main modification will appear in bin/server.ml. It will necessitate to understand how to interrupt the Lwt.run.
For exiting the server from the webpage, the situation is less clear.

* Improve the error messages of the lexer
  - [x] Print the line number where the error happens
  - [x] Print the bad character/string
  - [x] Print the name of the problematic file
The modification will be done in lib/RefML/lexer.mll, and possibly in the function `get_typed_opconf` and `get_typed_ienv` lib/RefML/refML.ml

* Improve the gamification of the tutorial
  - [ ] Remove the Evaluate button and always trigger it once we start a new level
  - [x] store in a session (using a cookie ?) the current level of the tutorial reached by the user, in order to restore it

* [x] Improve handling of errors when reading the integer in get_move in the CLI binary

* [x] Focus on ienv window when loading the page

* [x] Correct bug in the web interface regarding highlighting the top element of the stack in the ienv window when direct style option is selected.

* [x] Merge the interface of interactive_build.mli (used by the web interface), graph.mli and generate_trace.mli (used by the CLI executable) into a single one, with two implementations

* [ ] Distinguish divergence and failwith in the return of interactive_build in both front-ends.
  - We should instantiate IBUILD with a monad that provides various results
  - or we would allow interactive_build to return a type result M.m rather than unit M.m
 
* [ ] Restore the generation of a trace of moves via interactive_build in explore_cli
  - Using emit of the Output monad
  - It's difficult to change the type of run_interaction to get a module of the right type...

* [ ] Design a type for the return type of get_move representing the action performed by the user
  - the int type used currently is too simple
  - we could also encapsulate the return type of get_move in the monad M

* Provide a way to backtrack an action during the interaction
  - [ ] Generalize the get_move callback found in both Generate_trace.generate and Interactive_build.interactive_build functions to handle a backtrack event
  - [ ] Store the configurations reached after each interaction by the module
  - [ ] Find a generalization of the Lwt monad to handle this backtracking

* Provide a way for the user to enter with the keyboard the values (for example the integer) provided in the calls and returns
  - [ ] Introduce a notion of abstract value with typed holes, where the holes have to be completed by the user
  - [ ] Split the get_move callback in two functions: get_partial_move, and get_data

